Excellent shmup game. It easily takes one of my least favorite atari games and makes it one of my all time favorites. This game's got quite the pedigree - in addition to the original space invaders, taito also developed many well-loved shoot 'em ups like the Darius games, Metal Black, and RayForce/Layer Section/Galactic Attack. This history definitely shows in Infinity Gene - the game is packed full of delightful little throwbacks to their older works . likewise,  it's a blast to play and Zuntata absolutely killed it on the soundtrack! Unlike the PS3/Xbox360 version of this game, the Android version does not shift from 2D to 3D graphics after the level 3 stages. In fact, Levels 4 and beyond are simply not included in the game, and are instead replaced by bonus 2D stages. This is a fun, stylish game, but the Android version is simply too short compared to the console versions and cuts out one of the coolest thing about the game, the transition from 2D to 3D. I would not have purchased this game on Android had I known in advance.

This game seems to be totally nerfed on android.  I'm playing it on a Nexus 7 tablet.  It's lots of fun, but it feels unfinished.  I've read about other versions having other modes (challenge, music); this one only has the basic mode.  There's an option to turn off auto-shoot, but there's no control to shoot manually.  It screams of being a cheap port where the suits didn't want to spend the money to let the developers port over things that didn't port as cleanly when going from PS3, XBox and iOS.  That said, I bought this before I knew those versions existed.  The game occasionally crashes, but the data is all intact. Could be a problem with the OS; who knows, right?  I'd have given the game 5 stars if the manual shooting worked and if it had the other modes.  The lack of manual shooting really bugs me, but it's still loads of fun without it.  Definitely worth the $5.  2 nitpicks - 1. It's hard to tell what things your ship can touch (e.g., some enemies pass over you without hurting you) and 2. license checks stink on wifi only devices, especially when away from wifi.  There should be grace period (i.e., 5 day warning to connect).
